<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-147-230  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 147 230.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Journal of Systems Management  Feb 1990 v41 n2 p25(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Designing an EIS in a multidivisional environment.(ExecutiveInformation System)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fireworker, Robert B.; Zirkel, William.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>An executive information system (EIS) is one of the most usefulmodern business tools but a number of problems can arise whentrying to design and implement such a system, particularly in amultidivisional environment.andP;  The problems are most common in sixareas: politics, logistics, hardware, software, time and cost.andO;The political area is where the biggest problems are usuallyencountered, in terms of resistance to changes in the wayinformation flows through an organization.andP;  A case study ispresented of an EIS implemented in a Fortune 500 aerospace firm.andO;Six critical features were identified by the design team, whoworked closely with the firm's CEO: a top-down design approach,simplicity, fast response time, multi-level security, datavalidity, and simple data I-O procedures.andP;  Many of the problemsencountered in implementing an EIS can be overcome if a high-levelexecutive can be found to sponsor the system.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Case StudyGuidelinesTutorialExecutive Information Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   EIS system flow. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>